+#ifdef KLEE_BITCODE
+/* input-menu-pin v3 (transformations/path-explosion/input-menu-pin): the
+** sqlite3 CLI reads a SQL/dot-command script from a 20-byte symbolic stdin
+** (--sym-stdin 20). With those 20 bytes fully symbolic, KLEE fork-explodes in
+** the SQL tokenizer and NO state ever assembles a complete, terminating
+** statement (baseline: nurs:md2u 0 lines / 0 ktests) -- the
+** prepare/vdbe/btree execution engine is unreachable.
+**
+** This pins the symbolic stdin to ONE of a menu of complete, valid <=20-byte
+** programs, selected by a symbolic klee_range. KLEE forks ONCE on the selector
+** and explores EVERY menu entry in a SINGLE run (one bitcode, one KLEE run,
+** one manifest.json -- never a cross-run profraw union). Each branch:
+** (1) picks a concrete menu entry, (2) klee_assume()s the 20 symbolic stdin
+** bytes equal it (so the ktest replays that exact input on the native cov
+** binary), (3) concretizes the bytes so the downstream tokenize/parse/vdbe is
+** fork-free. Entries are PADDED to the full 20-byte width with trailing spaces
+** (no symbolic tail -- min-distance searchers would otherwise chase it and
+** never finish a path; md2u's baseline was 0).
+**
+** v3 adds the stdin-S_IFREG pin (see sqlite_klee_pin_stdin_regular below) on
+** top of v2's 71-entry menu. v2's bfs run lagged md2u by ~17.5k lines: KLEE's
+** POSIX model only *prefers* (klee_prefer_cex) S_IFREG for the symbolic stdin's
+** st_mode, so isatty(0) at main() entry still FORKS an S_IFCHR (character
+** device) branch. On that branch stdin_is_interactive=1 and the shell takes the
+** interactive early-bail path, so e.g. ".recover" covers 1,503 lines instead of
+** 25,616 -- and breadth-first banks exactly that shallow branch as a program's
+** covering-new ktest. Forcing st_mode==S_IFREG removes the interactive fork so
+** EVERY searcher takes the deep non-interactive path. (Same technique as
+** flex/menu-pin and bc.) Guarded by KLEE_BITCODE so the native coverage oracle
+** never sees klee_range / klee_assume. */
